header.gameNote: MISSOURI VALLEY CONF TR AT ST LOUIS MO

article.headline: Indiana State 72, Drake 63
article.story: ST. LOUIS (AP) -- David Moss scored 24 points to help Indiana State overcome a 10-point first-half deficit and beat Drake 72-63 Thursday in a play-in game in the Missouri Valley Conference Tournament. The 62 points in the second half were the most Indiana State has scored in a half this season. The Sycamores made 77 percent of their shots (23-of-30) in the second half. Indiana State, the No. 9 seed, will play No. 1 seed Wichita State at noon Friday in a quarterfinal game. Trent Wurtz scored 14 points and grabbed eight rebounds for the Sycamores (13-15). Moss scored just two points in the first half, but hit 9-of-10 field goals in the second. Eleven players scored for the Bulldogs (12-19), but only Al Stewart reached double figures with 10 points. Drake, the No. 8 seed, lost 11 of its final 12 games, including its last six. It was the first time the two teams met in the conference tournament. Drake had won nine of the last 11 games, including the last five meetings, against Indiana State. Drake outrebounded Indiana State 40-32 and made more turnovers, 23-17. The first half ended with Drake leading 19-10. Indiana State, which missed its first 14 field-goal attempts, did not connect until Darron Evans hit a short jumper with 10:15 remaining. The Sycamores, who began the season by winning their first eight games, ended the half hitting just 4-of-26 shots -- 15 percent. Indiana State had more turnovers in the half (13) than points. Drake didn't shoot much better, making 8-of-27 shots (29 percent), with 10 turnovers.
